Introduction to Computer Vision: Plant Seedlings Classification¶

Problem Statement¶

Context¶

In recent times, the field of agriculture has been in urgent need of modernizing, since the amount of manual work people need to put in to check if plants are growing correctly is still highly extensive. Despite several advances in agricultural technology, people working in the agricultural industry still need to have the ability to sort and recognize different plants and weeds, which takes a lot of time and effort in the long term. The potential is ripe for this trillion-dollar industry to be greatly impacted by technological innovations that cut down on the requirement for manual labor, and this is where Artificial Intelligence can actually benefit the workers in this field, as the time and energy required to identify plant seedlings will be greatly shortened by the use of AI and Deep Learning. The ability to do so far more efficiently and even more effectively than experienced manual labor, could lead to better crop yields, the freeing up of human inolvement for higher-order agricultural decision making, and in the long term will result in more sustainable environmental practices in agriculture as well.

Objective¶

The aim of this project is to Build a Convolutional Neural Netowrk to classify plant seedlings into their respective categories.

Data Dictionary¶

The Aarhus University Signal Processing group, in collaboration with the University of Southern Denmark, has recently released a dataset containing images of unique plants belonging to 12 different species.

  • The dataset can be download from Olympus.
  • The data file names are:
    • images.npy
    • Label.csv

  • Due to the large volume of data, the images were converted to the images.npy file and the labels are also put into Labels.csv, so that you can work on the data/project seamlessly without having to worry about the high data volume.

  • The goal of the project is to create a classifier capable of determining a plant's species from an image.

List of Species

  • Black-grass
  • Charlock
  • Cleavers
  • Common Chickweed
  • Common Wheat
  • Fat Hen
  • Loose Silky-bent
  • Maize
  • Scentless Mayweed
  • Shepherds Purse
  • Small-flowered Cranesbill
  • Sugar beet

def plot_images(images,labels):
  num_classes=10                                                                  # Number of Classes
  categories=np.unique(labels)
  keys=dict(labels['Label'])                                                      # Obtaing the unique classes from y_train
  rows = 3                                                                        # Defining number of rows=3
  cols = 4                                                                        # Defining number of columns=4
  fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))                                               # Defining the figure size to 10x8
  for i in range(cols):
      for j in range(rows):
          random_index = np.random.randint(0, len(labels))                        # Generating random indices from the data and plotting the images
          ax = fig.add_subplot(rows, cols, i * rows + j + 1)                      # Adding subplots with 3 rows and 4 columns
          ax.imshow(images[random_index, :])                                      # Plotting the image
          ax.set_title(keys[random_index])
  plt.show()

Resize the images¶

As the size of the images is large, it may be computationally expensive to train on these larger images; therefore, it is preferable to reduce the image size from 128 to 64.

In [12]:
images_decreased=[]
height = 64  # Define the height as 64
width = 64   # Define the width as 64
dimensions = (width, height)
for i in range(len(images)):
  images_decreased.append(cv2.resize(images[i], dimensions, interpolation=cv2.INTER_LINEAR))

  • Before you proceed to build a model, you need to split the data into train, test, and validation to be able to evaluate the model that you build on the train data
  • You'll have to encode categorical features and scale the pixel values.
  • You will build a model using the train data and then check its performance

Observations¶

Training Dataset:

  • It contains 3,847 samples.
  • Each image in the training set has dimensions of 64x64 pixels and includes color information (RGB).
  • The labels, indicating the categories, are in a binary format with one column.

Validation Dataset:

  • This dataset, with 428 samples, is separate from the training set.
  • Similar to the training set, each image is 64x64 pixels with RGB color.
  • The labels are also in a binary format with one column.

Testing Dataset:

  • Reserved for evaluating the model's performance on new, unseen data.
  • It consists of 475 samples, sharing the same image dimensions and label format as the training and validation sets.

In summary, these datasets are appropriately divided for training, validation, and testing purposes. The images are all standardized to 64x64 pixels with RGB color, and the labels follow a binary format for classification.

Each sample is represented by a one-hot encoded array indicating its class. The sizes of the encoded label arrays match the corresponding sizes of the datasets.

Data Normalization¶

Given that the pixel values in the images span from 0 to 255, our normalization approach involves scaling. Specifically, we will standardize the images by dividing all pixel values by 255, ensuring that the resulting values fall within the range of 0 to 1.

In [22]:
X_train_normalized = X_train.astype('float32') / 255.0
X_val_normalized = X_val.astype('float32') / 255.0
X_test_normalized = X_test.astype('float32') / 255.0

In [25]:
# Intializing a sequential model
model1 = Sequential()

# Adding the first conv layer with 128 filters and kernel size 3x3, padding 'same' provides the output size same as the input size
# Input_shape denotes input image dimension of images
model1.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding="same", input_shape=(64, 64, 3)))

# Adding the max pooling to reduce the size of output of the first conv layer
model1.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2), padding='same'))

# Creating two similar convolution and max-pooling layers activation = relu
model1.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding="same"))
model1.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2), padding='same'))

model1.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding="same"))
model1.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2), padding='same'))

# Flattening the output of the conv layer after max pooling to make it ready for creating dense connections
model1.add(Flatten())

# Adding a fully connected dense layer with 16 neurons
model1.add(Dense(16, activation='relu'))
model1.add(Dropout(0.3))

# Adding the output layer with 12 neurons and activation function as softmax since this is a multi-class classification problem
model1.add(Dense(12, activation='softmax'))

# Using the Adam Optimizer
opt = Adam()

# Compiling the model using categorical cross-entropy for loss function
model1.compile(optimizer=opt, loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

# Generating the summary of the model
model1.summary()

Observations:¶

The model with sequential architecture comprising various layers:

  1. Convolutional Layer 1: Generates an output shape of (64, 64, 128) with 3,584 parameters.
  2. Max Pooling Layer 1: Reduces dimensions to (32, 32, 128) without introducing new trainable parameters.
  3. Convolutional Layer 2: Produces an output shape of (32, 32, 64) with 73,792 parameters.
  4. Max Pooling Layer 2: Further reduces dimensions to (16, 16, 64) without adding trainable parameters.
  5. Convolutional Layer 3: Yields an output shape of (16, 16, 32) with 18,464 parameters.
  6. Max Pooling Layer 3: Reduces dimensions to (8, 8, 32) without introducing new trainable parameters.
  7. Flatten Layer: Flattens the output to (2048) with no trainable parameters.
  8. Dense Layer 1: A fully connected layer with 32,784 parameters and 16 neurons.
  9. Dropout Layer: Implements dropout regularization with no additional trainable parameters.
  10. Dense Layer 2: Another fully connected layer with 204 parameters and 12 neurons, representing the final output classes.

The model encompasses a total of 128,828 parameters, all of which are trainable. It utilizes convolutional and pooling layers to capture hierarchical features in the input data, followed by dense layers for classification. The incorporation of a dropout layer aims to prevent overfitting during the training process.

Model Performance Improvement¶

Reducing the Learning Rate:

ReduceLRonPlateau() is a function that will be used to decrease the learning rate by some factor, if the loss is not decreasing for some time. This may start decreasing the loss at a smaller learning rate. There is a possibility that the loss may still not decrease. This may lead to executing the learning rate reduction again in an attempt to achieve a lower loss.

In [32]:
# Code to monitor val_accuracy
learning_rate_reduction = ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor='val_accuracy',
                                            patience=3,
                                            verbose=1,
                                            factor=0.5,
                                            min_lr=0.00001)

# Intializing a sequential model
model2 = Sequential()

# Complete the code to add the first conv layer with 64 filters and kernel size 3x3, padding 'same' provides the output size same as the input size
# Input_shape denotes input image dimension images
model2.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding="same", input_shape=(64, 64, 3)))

# Complete the code to add max pooling to reduce the size of output of first conv layer
model2.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2), padding='same'))

model2.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding="same"))
model2.add(MaxPooling2D((2, 2), padding='same'))
model2.add(BatchNormalization())

# flattening the output of the conv layer after max pooling to make it ready for creating dense connections
model2.add(Flatten())

# Adding a fully connected dense layer with 16 neurons
model2.add(Dense(16, activation='relu'))

# Complete the code to add dropout with dropout_rate=0.3
model2.add(Dropout(0.3))
# Complete the code to add the output layer with 12 neurons and activation functions as softmax since this is a multi-class classification problem
model2.add(Dense(12, activation='softmax'))

# Complete the code to initialize Adam Optimimzer
opt = Adam()
# Complete the code to Compile model
model2.compile(optimizer=opt, loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

# Generating the summary of the model
model2.summary()

Observations¶

  1. Structure:

    • The model follows a Sequential structure, implying a sequential arrangement of layers.

  2. Convolutional Layers:

    • The initial convolutional layer (conv2d) employs 64 filters with a (3, 3) kernel, resulting in an output shape of (64, 64, 64).
    • The subsequent convolutional layer (conv2d_1) utilizes 32 filters with a (3, 3) kernel, producing an output shape of (32, 32, 32).

  3. Pooling Layers:

    • Max pooling is implemented after each convolutional layer through max_pooling2d. The first pooling layer reduces the output shape to (32, 32, 64), followed by the second layer, which further reduces it to (16, 16, 32).

  4. Batch Normalization:

    • batch_normalization is applied post the second pooling layer, contributing to stability and speed during training.

  5. Flatten Layer:

    • The flatten layer (flatten) reshapes the output from preceding layers into a one-dimensional array, comprising 8192 elements.

  6. Dense Layers:

    • The initial dense layer (dense) comprises 16 units, succeeded by a dropout layer (dropout) with a dropout rate of 0 (indicating no dropout).
    • The ultimate dense layer (dense_1) encompasses 12 units, representing the output classes.

  7. Total Parameters:

    • The model encompasses a total of 151,676 parameters, with 151,612 being trainable and 64 non-trainable.

In essence, this model is structured with convolutional layers for feature extraction, pooling layers for downsampling, batch normalization for stability, and dense layers for classification. The architecture is tailored for image classification, specifically with 12 output classes.

Final model selection¶

In [44]:
# Evaluating model1

# Choose the better model based on test accuracy
final_model = model1 if accuracy_model1[1] > accuracy_model2[1] else model2

Actionable Insights and Business Recommendations¶

Actionable Insights and Business Recommendations:

Model Selection: Model2, incorporating advanced techniques like batch normalization and dropout, demonstrates superior performance compared to Model1 on the test set. Therefore, it is advisable to opt for Model2 for deployment.

Data Augmentation: Utilizing data augmentation to artificially expand the training dataset is a commendable practice, enhancing the model's ability to generalize to unseen data.

Class Distribution: While the dataset exhibits a relatively balanced distribution across multiple classes, some classes have fewer samples, potentially impacting the model's performance on those specific classes.

Confusion Matrix Analysis: Analyzing the confusion matrix provides valuable insights into the model's performance across individual classes. Variations in precision and recall metrics highlight areas for potential improvement.

Model Improvement Strategies: Fine-tuning the model involves adjusting hyperparameters like learning rate, batch size, and epochs. Exploring alternative architectures, including deeper networks or leveraging pre-trained models for feature extraction, can further enhance performance. Consider advanced techniques such as transfer learning to capitalize on knowledge from models trained on larger datasets.

Learning Rate Adjustment: Model2 implements learning rate reduction on plateaus, a pivotal technique for accelerating convergence and enhancing generalization. Continuous monitoring of the learning rate during training is recommended to ensure adaptability to progress.

Image Preprocessing: Resizing images to 64x64 pixels reduces computational complexity. Experimenting with different preprocessing techniques or resolutions may offer insights into their impact on model performance.

Business Recommendations: Deploy the model for automated plant species classification in real-world scenarios. Regularly monitor model performance and consider retraining with new data to adapt to changing conditions. Prioritize data collection, particularly for classes with limited samples, to strengthen the model's ability to differentiate between underrepresented classes.

User Interface and Interpretability: Develop an intuitive interface for user interaction, providing insights into predictions and model confidence. Implement interpretability techniques to understand the features influencing predictions, especially for critical decisions.

Collaboration with Domain Experts: Engage with botanists or domain experts to enhance the model's accuracy and interpretability. Gathering domain knowledge is essential for comprehending challenges in real-world plant species classification. Continuous monitoring and improvement are crucial for sustaining the model's effectiveness. Consider the ethical implications of deployment, ensuring transparent communication with end-users regarding the model's capabilities and limitations.
